title: dlopen failed for libonnxruntime4j_jni.so library
body:
**Describe the bug**
I download the [onnxruntime-android-1.11.0.aar](https://repo1.maven.org/maven2/com/microsoft/onnxruntime/onnxruntime-android/1.11.0/onnxruntime-android-1.11.0.aar") library and unzip to get C++ headers and jni C++, C shared libraries.  In jni folder, each ABI version has 2 shared libraries files: libonnxruntime.so, libonnxruntime4j_jni.so.
The Cmake looks like 
```
add_library(lib_onnx_jni SHARED IMPORTED)
set_target_properties(lib_onnx_jni PROPERTIES IMPORTED_LOCATION
        ${distribution_DIR}/${ANDROID_ABI}/libonnxruntime4j_jni.so)

add_library(lib_onnx_runtime SHARED IMPORTED)
set_target_properties(lib_onnx_runtime PROPERTIES IMPORTED_LOCATION
        ${distribution_DIR}/${ANDROID_ABI}/libonnxruntime.so)

target_link_libraries(share_name
                      android
                    lib_onnx_jni
                    lib_onnx_runtime
                      ${log-lib})
```
When I try to build a shared library call **share_name** it raises FATAL EXCEPTION
 `   java.lang.UnsatisfiedLinkError: dlopen failed: library "C:/Users/... onnx/app/src/main/cc/../../../../libraries/onnxruntime/jni/arm64-v8a/libonnxruntime4j_jni.so"`


However, when I removed **lib_onnx_jni** , the project can compile normally and it managed to find **lib_onnx_runtime**
So questions: Do I need to have libonnxruntime4j_jni.so for C++ application in Android, since there are 2 shared libraries here. 
Thanks.

Current model tests will list all the unit tests on the CI log.

labels.name: platform:web

body:
**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
It's almost never a good idea to run heavy computation on the main thread, so it seems like most of the time people would want to set this to true.

Perhaps the idea was that the inference session may sometimes be created by the developer inside a worker, and the extra layer of indirection would then be a waste? In that case I think the burden should be on those developers to find/understand/adjust the options to suit their use case, since it's likely a less common situation, and also is not really a big deal (having an extra, unnecessary worker) compared to lagging the main thread.

Perhaps, to get the best of both worlds, the library could detect whether it's running on the main thread ([like this](https://stackoverflow.com/a/18002694)) and default to proxying via a worker if so. But unless I'm missing something here I think defaulting to creating the proxy worker is fine.

**Describe the solution you'd like**
If most users should be setting `ort.env.wasm.proxy` to `true`, then that should be the default value.

**Describe alternatives you've considered**
Another possibility is to adjust the default based on whether it's executing on the main thread vs. the worker.

title: QlinearConv threading adjustments
body:
**Description**: 
QLinearConv thread job partition adjustment and general threading impl adjustments

1. Existing 4x task granularity for task partitioning on hybrid CPUs is not sufficient to compensate the difference of VNNI instructions
throughput between performance and efficient cores. This patch...

  * Increases granularity for QLinearConv by 2x, to have 2x more tasks
  with 2x smaller output count

  * Limits QLinearConv task count from above, to avoid output count per
  task getting smaller than kernel's capability

  * Remove hardcoded task count for QLineConv as it limited scaling on
  16+ cores CP


2. Remove unneeded PAUSE instruction (0.1-0.2 usec latency) after a worker thread finds a task to execute.

3. Currently in "auto affinity" mode the worker threads are affinized to cores 0..(N-1), leaving the very last core for the main thread. This patch preserves core #0 for the main thread, and affinizes the worker threads to cores 1..N.

title: NonZero shape inference behavior with scalar input mismatches ONNX and PyTorch

labels.name: core runtime
labels.description: issues related to core runtime

body:
**Describe the bug**
For the case of NonZero with scalar input, ONNXRuntime will infer shape (1, N), which is different from PyTorch and ONNX's shape inference (0, N). The reason is probably because ONNXRuntime followed ONNX's spec for Nonzero: `NonZero behaves similar to numpy.nonzero`. In this case Numpy will produce shape (1, N) for scalar input, but this behavior will be deprecated in the future according to the [document](https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/generated/numpy.nonzero.html). However, ONNX shape inference infers shape as (0, N), which has same logic as PyTorch. (dimension should be zero)

Here is the summary for different libraries behavior:
- PyTorch
```
import torch
torch.nonzero(torch.tensor(0))
# tensor([], size=(0, 0), dtype=torch.int64)
torch.nonzero(torch.tensor(1))
# tensor([], size=(1, 0), dtype=torch.int64)
```
- TensorFlow
```
import tensorflow
tensorflow.where(tensorflow.constant(0))
# InvalidArgumentError: WhereOp : Unhandled input dimensions: 0 [Op:Where]
tensorflow.where(tensorflow.constant(1))
# InvalidArgumentError: WhereOp : Unhandled input dimensions: 0 [Op:Where]
```
- NumPy
```
import numpy as np
np.array(np.nonzero(0))
# array([], shape=(1, 0), dtype=int64)
np.array(np.nonzero(1))
# array([[0]]), shape (1, 1)
```

To sum up, it seems that ONNX shape inference follows PyTorch's behavior, TensorFlow does not allow scalar input for Where (NonZero-like operator in TensorFlow). ONNXRuntime follows NumPy's behavior.


Since ONNX follows PyTorch and TensorFlow even does not allow scalar input. And also NumPy behavior will be deprecated. IMO, a proper direction should be following upstream like PyTorch or TensorFlow to prevent users' confusion. Therefore ONNX will update NonZero's spec to resolve ambiguity, saying that scalar input will produce shape as (0, N), which is different from current NumPy's behavior.

Although I think it shouldn't be a popular case since most of developers would probably follow PyTorch and TensorFlow, this will very likely break backwards compatibility in ORT so we have open questions [here](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/pull/4113#issuecomment-1099544587) from @gramalingam:
- Does anyone want the NumPy behavior?
- How should ONNXRuntime handle this mismatch between ONNX (and PyTorch)?

Assuming some users want it, the best solution seems an upward compatible extension by adding an attribute "treat_0D_as_1D", which if set to 1 (true), will produce the NumPy behavior.
 

Related discussion: https://github.com/onnx/onnx/pull/4113.

**Urgency**
None

**To Reproduce**
Build ORT and run onnxruntime_test_all --gtest_filter='NonZeroOpTest.Scalar'.
Currently the test triggers a shape inference failure which results in a warning being logged. Giving scalar input, ONNX shape inference produces shape (0, N), but ORT produces (1, N).

**Expected behavior**
It should produce shape (0, N), same as ONNX and PyTorch.

title: Data type and shape aware allocation
body:
**Description**:

This is splitted from dev/opencl branch. This PR adds a new optional interface to IAllocator for allocating Image/Texture like memeory.

The packing process to fit high dimensional tensor into a Texture, say, 2D texture, is left for EP impl.

The returned ptr can be taken as an opaque ptr/handle/object. It shares some similarity with pointers which are created from `cudaMalloc` in CUDA EP: The host cannot access the content directly via dereferencing. In the case of Texture memory ptr, it is more restrictive that pointer arithmetic is allowed.  So the Tensor only holds the opaque ptr for lifetime management.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
  Previously, allocation can only be size based, however, in APIs that can leverage the GPU compute power, such as OpenCL, OpenGL, Vulkan, DirectX, CUDA, there exists another memory kind that is related with Texture/Surface/Image. The name may vary, but they share the common characteristic that they leverage Texture Memory Unit to accelerate accessing. They thus need the datatype and shape information to be correctly setup.

title: IOBinding doesn't release the Python GIL
body:
It appears that in ONNXRuntime latest version (v1.11.0), running a model with IOBinding doesn't release the Python GIL when invoking `run_with_iobinding()`. This has a significantly negative impact on performance because it blocks all other Python threads from executing while inference is running. As far as I understand here is the relevant code:

https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/b713855a980056d89a1e550ad81dc3c19573d7a0/onnxruntime/python/onnxruntime_pybind_state.cc#L1498-L1506

As you can see, with the classic `run` method the GIL is properly released:

https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/b713855a980056d89a1e550ad81dc3c19573d7a0/onnxruntime/python/onnxruntime_pybind_state.cc#L1395-L1402

title: Add ATen export and gradient for torch.max/min
body:
**Description**: Add ATen export and gradient for `torch.max`/`min`

**Motivation and Context**
There are currently three cases in exporting `torch.max`:
1. `torch.max(input)`, exported as `ReduceMax`
2. `torch.max(input, other)`, exported as `Max`
3. `torch.max(input, dim, keepdim)`, exported as `ReduceMax`+`ArgMax`

We already have gradient for `Max`. This change deals with cases 1 and 3. Likewise for `torch.min`.

title: Contrib ops for TRT plugin: Disentangled Attention Plugin
body:
**Description**

Registers a new contrib op for TensorRT plugin: DisentangledAttentionPlugin, which is a new attention design in Microsoft's DeBERTa model.

**Motivation and Context**
* TensorRT plugins allow fused and efficient execution of common complex operations not natively supported by TensorRT.
An ONNX graph that has been modified to use TensorRT plugins ops will normally not run in ORT because it fails graph validation.
* This PR implements contrib ops for these operations so that ORT accepts them, and the TRT-EP backend can execute them.
* This PR follows a previous example [here](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/9486) for other TensorRT plugins.

**Notes**
* This PR also needs a small change in the onnx-tensorrt dependency (the NVIDIA ONNX parser, example shown [here](https://github.com/symphonylyh/onnx-tensorrt/commit/0510e54ed2d99a4fcfc619a5a97b7b682344a07e)), which is not publicly released yet. Currently, this PR contains a commit that changes the `cmake/external/onnx-tensorrt` submodule url. Ideally, merging of this PR should probably wait until ORT with TensorRT >= v8.2.4 support is fully merged first.
* Collaboration with @stevenlix. Request for review.
